	<td class="alt2">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Healing in Everquest</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" color="" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><b>NOTE TO THOSE JOINING US HERE AT THE CONVENANT:</b><br />
This thread was originally started in our General section before this new forum went live. It is NOT by any means representative of the kind of moderation you will see here - but merely forwarded here as a reference.<br />
<br />
When I get some time, I'll organize the thoughts that are in this thread and then probably move it somewheres else.<br />
<br />
Please forgive me for confusing those who thought this is an example of the kind of moderation you can expect here in the Convenant. <i>-- Chenier</i><br />
<br />
***********************<br />
<br />
As Chenier suggested in the Summit discussion thread I hope to start a constructive discussion of healing in Everquest without descending into class bashing or 'if they get a cookie I want a cookie also' mentality. I have not much hope, but maybe we can surprise ourselves with our own maturity.<br />
<br />
That said, I would like to start with a discussion just what healing in Everquest is, and if we can agree on that we can perhaps move on to talk about the game mechanics as the apply to/require healing.<br />
<br />
Please try to avoid class specific examples if at all possible. They tend to derail a conversation. There has been a 88+ page thread on healing before that actually seemed to go somewhere before being totally derailed for a long while in name-calling and thinly veiled personal flames.<br />
Certainly avoid to ask for class specific changes. If those are necessary it is my hope that as the picture gets clearer it also becomes obvious where the bottlenecks are and what the most logical way to solve them.<br />
Please try to stick to 'I think it is more like [this] because of [this]' type of replies rather than the 'Only an idiot would believe [this]' flamebait.<br />
<br />
* * * * * * * * *<br />
<br />
That said I would like to begin with writing out the different types of healing that I see in Everquest.<br />
Most people at least on this board say there are 5 types of heal, but personally I believe there are 6:<br />
<br />
Direct healing<br />
This can be split into three types:<br />
<br />
1 - Big Heals. Slow casting and/or long recovery heals for large amounts of HP. The kind of heals that CH rotations are based on. The bandaging that every class can do falls into this category also.<br />
<br />
2- Fast Heals. Less powerful but considerably faster to cast, andcan be casted more frequently. Also known as Spam Heals.<br />
<br />
3- Heal over Time. Restoring a number of hitpoints every tick for a longer period of time. Generally heals the least, but has the advantage that things can be done after casting this type of healing as it does not require attention from the healer.<br />
<br />
Indirect healing<br />
This too can be split into three types:<br />
<br />
4- Mitigation. Any spell/skill that limits or prevents damage. A slowed monster that swings half as often is effectively the same as healing half the damage done each time. A mezzed monster is in effect the same as giving the tank infinite heal for the duration.<br />
<br />
5- Hitpoint buffs. Giving somebody 10000 hitpoints is the same as healing for that much. The difference is that it typically can only be done once. it is possible though to create version that is renewable, but then the difference with direct healing is negliceable.<br />
<br />
6- Inverse damage shield. Transfering some of the damage done to a monster to the target of the shield as hitpoints.<br />
<br />
These 6 types of healing can come in single target, group and raid variety, though not all of those are currently existing in the game. Technically there would also be self-only versions, but I am not certain if that type of healing should be discussed in the light of the question Chenier asked as they only apply to solo. If it needs to be discussed I would prefer to delegate it to a separate thread.<br />
<br />
<br />
This gives a total of 18 different types of healing (or 12 if you ignore the currently non-existent raid healing spells), each of which has its typical use in the game<br />
<br />
<br />
* * * * * * * * *<br />
<br />
Is the above a good breakdown of healing in Everquest, or did I miss something obvious that should be taken into consideration? Please constructive criticism only. If you agree I would like to hear it also, but after one or two of those I think everybody understands.<br />
<br />
<br />
Erianaiel</div>
