</div><br />
<br />
I am not familiar with Divine Arbitration nor what exactly it does. Could you please explain?<br />
<br />
Long Range Heals. I think I see your point, but if you would, could you explain in brief (similar to the two line descriptions I gave for the categories I came up with) why it should be considered a different form of direct healing?<br />
<br />
Divine Intervention. Again I am not really familiar with this spell, could you please explain to me what it does, and why spells of this type should be considered a different type of healing and not e.g. a form of damage mitigation or hitpoint buff?<br />
<br />
Damage absorbers, I think should be considered a form of mitigation. A fixed amount of damage gets removed from attacks that actually hit similar to slow, that takes off a percentage. Unless I am mistaken?<br />
<br />
Regen is not different from healing over time and I would put it in that category. Again, unless I am much mistaken, in which case I would like to hear how and why.<br />
<br />
<br />
Where I would like to go with this is: after we can agree on what *types* of healing there are, we can then see what types of healing are *needed* throughout the came in various encounters, for groups and for raids. Again without talking about classes in specific. Just [this] monster/encounter needs [this] and [this] healing because of [this], and for [this] playstyle in [this] area [this] type of healing is most important.<br />
<br />
Knowing that, we can finally decide *if* there are healing gaps for the different classes in certain age ranges or zones, and if so *what* they are and how big they are. However, that part of the discussion is a way in the future.<br />
<br />
<br />
Erianaiel</div>
