	<td class="alt2">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>I don't know how well it is possible to keep the specific classes out of the discussion and just focus on the healing component alone - might be a tough cookie to crack.<br />
<br />
What I think pretty much everyone can agree on is that Complete Healing is as much of a blessing as it is a curse. <br />
<br />
It's a blessing because up until recently, complete was complete. Whoever got hit with it, was back up to full. They did tamper a bit with it in Luclin (where they added curses that reduced healing efficiency), but that never really fleshed out. Now, in the later expansions (GoD primarily), the time needed to cast a CHeal is often too long and people need to resort to using faster - but (much) less efficient - healing power to keep the group alive. It should be noted that GoD was tailored for higher levels, which implies that the recent down-tuning and the upcoming lvl 70 will once again enable the use of the most efficient heal out there to be used effectively: Complete Healing.<br />
<br />
It's a curse because of its efficiency, as well. Based on that aspect alone, it has hampered the development of interesting healing spells more than anything else. Because let's face it, who in his right mind would ever use a spell less efficient than CHeal, if there's no need to? So not only did they have to develop these other healing spells, they also had to artificially create encounters that made the use of CHeals a bit awkward to say the least. When the first signals of GoD came out in the open, I thought they had finally found something; but with the recent tuning, I have been using CHeals again in the Sewer trials. Not because I want it so bad, but simply because of the efficiency of the spell far outweighing that of any other - conserving mana in the long run.<br />
<br />
Back when Velious was released, they should have changed Complete Healing. Instead, they tailored the encounters around it, which saw the rise of the Complete Heal chain. To off-set the enormous healing power of a CHeal chain, mobs were made to do vast amounts of damage. This in fact resulted in a downward spiral; players simply started adding more Clerics to the chain at shorter intervals. Next expansions saw mobs with more HPs and DPS yet. Luclin boss fights are often longer than 15 minutes simply due to the vast amount of hitpoints and high AC. And Xegony is pure evil. A detrimental side effect is that this keeps Clerics locked into one and the same thing throughout the whole encounter: casting that Complete Heal at set intervals, over a long duration and unable to do anything else. Some Clerics like this, others do not. Personally, I don't mind it, but would like to have other options as well - and in fact, since I am usually setting up the healing routines for our raids, I have been trying fast heals instead of a CHeal chain as well. It works, but the fight can't last too long, as fast heals have an inferior mana efficiency to CHealing and healers will be dry before long.<br />
<br />
If any attempt were made to change the way healing is currently done, then I think they need to do one thing: get rid of Complete Healing. With that one out of the way, they can really flesh out the three healing classes, give each comparable healing power, but in different areas. This will be a huge undertaking, however, as they not only need to consider class balance between the healers, they will also need to rework ALL encounters since Velious that depend on a CHeal chain. And therein really lies the problem: since the Cheal "curse" was not properly recognised during the Velious era, it has become embedded in the core of what Everquest is today. The changes therefore affect the fundaments of the game as a whole.<br />
<br />
Personally, I would really love to see them have the guts and dive into it, make the changes needed. It will shake the healers tree quite a bit and I am sure some will fall out. But I think the tree won't end up top-heavy anymore.<br />
<br />
- Exarch Kaysha Soulsinger<br />
Archon of Erollisi Marr<br />
<br />
Keadarie Wolfpaws<br />
Druid of Tunare</div>
